liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Australian share market has ended in the red as expectations increase of more interest rate rises following a hawkish speech today from RBA governor Philip Lowe. New data showed that Australia's economy slowed over the first few months of the year, with gross domestic product expanding just 0.2 per cent over the March quarter, and by 2.3 per cent over the year. The Australian dollar fell from today's high of 66.89 US cents to 66.66 US cents. The ASX 200 index lost 0.2 per cent to 7,118 with banks and energy stocks leading the losses. Beach Energy slumped 8.1 per cent after saying it would abandon an exploration well in WA after recovering no gas. Viva Energy (-2.8 per cent) also fell after the failure of a crane led to a compressor being dropped causing damage at its refinery in Geelong in Victoria. Viva says it estimates will take up to 3 months to repair the damage with losses of up to $35 million each month. Medical devices firm Polynovo (+15.8 per cent) surged after making record monthly sales of $7.2 million.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Australian market loses its gains on slowing economy

children.content: The Australian share market has ended in the red as expectations increase of more interest rate rises following a hawkish speech today from RBA governor Philip Lowe.

New data showed that Australia's economy slowed over the first few months of the year, with gross domestic product expanding just 0.2 per cent over the March quarter, and by 2.3 per cent over the year.
The Australian dollar fell from today's high of 66.89 US cents to 66.66 US cents.
The ASX 200 index lost 0.2 per cent to 7,118 with banks and energy stocks leading the losses.
Beach Energy slumped 8.1 per cent after saying it would abandon an exploration well in WA after recovering no gas.
Viva Energy (-2.8 per cent) also fell after the failure of a crane led to a compressor being dropped causing damage at its refinery in Geelong in Victoria.
Viva says it estimates will take up to 3 months to repair the damage with losses of up to $35 million each month.
Medical devices firm Polynovo (+15.8 per cent) surged after making record monthly sales of $7.2 million.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The administrators of weight loss firm Jenny Craig have recommended that the business be wound up because they couldn't find a buyer. Jenny Craig's 91 stores in Australia and New Zealand have closed and staff will be made redundant. FTI Consulting say they were unable to find a buyer for the business despite 15 interested parties, four of whom submitted offers. They will recommend to creditors that the business be liquidated at a creditors' meeting next week. Jenny Craig's online business will be sold to healthcare technology company Eucalyptus. "Despite best efforts, the administrators were unable to find a buyer for the physical stores and employees of the  Australian and New Zealand business," the administrators said. " The administrators have today advised all of the employees in Australia New  Zealand that a sale of the business with the stores continuing to trade and staff continuing their employment has  not been achievable." " This has resulted in a decision to immediately cease trading from stores and employees being  made redundant, which is an unfortunate outcome and one which the administrators had sought to avoid." FTI were called in as voluntary liquidators last month to try and sell the Australian and New Zealand business. Jenny Craig's US business went under last month. Here's more from business reporter Rhianna Whitson.
